{"cursor":"4105","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox royalty\n| type = monarch name = OrdoÃ±o IV image = Ordono IV of Leon big.jpg imgw = 200px\n| caption = succession = King of LeÃ³n reign = 958–960 coronation =\n| predecessor = Sancho I successor = Sancho I spouse = Urraca FernÃ¡ndez issue =\n| issue-link = issue-pipe = full name = house = Beni Alfons house-type = Dynasty\n| father = Alfonso IV of LeÃ³n mother = Oneca SÃ¡nchez of Pamplona birth_date = c.\n| 926 birth_place = death_date = c. 962 or 963 death_place = CÃ³rdoba\n| burial_place = Basilica of San Isidoro religion = Roman Catholicism }}\n'OrdoÃ±o IV', called 'the Wicked' or 'the Bad' (c. 926âCÃ³rdoba, c. 962 or 963)\nwas the king of LeÃ³n from 958 until 960, interrupting the reign of Sancho the\nFat for a two-year period.\n\nHe was the son of Alfonso IV of LeÃ³n and his queen, Oneca SÃ¡nchez of\nPamplona, Some modern scholars instead believe him to have been son of\nAlfonso FrÃ³ilaz. and nephew of Ramiro II of LeÃ³n and of GarcÃ­a SÃ¡nchez I\nof Pamplona.\n\nIn 958, two years into the reign of Sancho I of LeÃ³n, he benefited from a\nrebellion of the nobility that would succeed in briefly placing him on the\nthrone. The Leonese nobles, as well as the disaffected Galician and Castilian\nones, had grown sick of the obese Sancho. He received particular help in this\nfrom his brother-in-law, count FernÃ¡n GonzÃ¡lez of Castile, whose daughter he\nmarried. However, count FernÃ¡n was defeated through Navarrese intervention on\nSancho's behalf in 960, and OrdoÃ±o was forced out. Upon losing his throne,\nOrdoÃ±o fled first to Asturias, then Burgos, where he abandoned his wife. This\nlost him the support of FernÃ¡n GonzÃ¡lez, who allied himself with GarcÃ­a SÃ¡nchez\nI of Pamplona. The Castilian count sent OrdoÃ±o to Ghalib al-Nasiri, commander of\nthe 'Middle Frontier' in Medinaceli, from whom he was passed on to the court of\nthe caliph of CÃ³rdoba. There he submitted and made plea for aid. The caliph at\nfirst offered him help, but this led his rival Sancho likewise to offer his\nsubmission, thereby neutralizing any benefit to the caliph helping OrdoÃ±o, who\ndied in Cordoba, still dethroned.\n\nDuring the short period of his reign, he was married, for political reasons, to\nUrraca, daughter of FernÃ¡n GonzÃ¡lez and formerly wife of his cousin OrdoÃ±o III\nof LeÃ³n. After OrdoÃ±o IV abandoned her, she would remarry to Sancho II of\nPamplona. According to chronicler Sampiro, she bore OrdoÃ±o IV two children, but\ntheir identity is not known with certainty. Chronicler Ibn Hayyan assigns him a\nson GarcÃ­a, but given that Urraca had a son of that name, the future king GarcÃ­a\nSÃ¡nchez II of Pamplona by her third husband, Ibn Hayyan may have mistaken this\nstep-son for a son. Likewise, a minority of modern scholars consider Vermudo II\nof LeÃ³n to have been son of OrdoÃ±o IV by Urraca rather than OrdoÃ±o III of LeÃ³n.\n","linknr":150,"url":"Ordoño_IV_of_León","recorded":1375075538,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Ordo%C3%B1o_IV_of_Le%C3%B3n&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Ordo%C3%B1o_IV_of_Le%C3%B3n&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/File:Translation_to_english_arrow.svg","/